description.narrative:
The Human Sciences Research Council (HSRC) Year 3 activities focus on gaps identified in the “Key Populations, Key Solutions” report compiled by the Desmond Tutu HIV Foundation.  Four key priority areas have been defined, which include:
1. A rapid assessment of the acceptability of combination HIV prevention programmes for key populations (KPs) highlighting harm reduction strategies; 
2. Costing for provision of HIV combination prevention programmes for KPs; 
3. stigma and discrimination of people living with HIV in South Africa, with a focus on KPs  
4. An evaluation of the acceptability and uptake of a combination HIV prevention package of biomedical, behavioral, and community-level HIV prevention interventions and services for MSM in South Africa (The Sibanye Health Project). Partnerships established in Year 1 and Year 2 with relevant HIV prevention services that work with KPs and representatives of provincial and local Departments of Health in Cape Town, Johannesburg, and Durban will be retained for Year 3 activities. In addition, HSRC was awarded KP Implementation Science funds to evaluate leveraging community and peer-based approaches to enhance the continuum of HIV care from awareness of HIV status to viral suppression among MSM living with HIV in SA.
